
com.example.app
    ├── config
    │   └── DatabaseConfig.java
    ├── dao
    │   └── UserDao.java
    │   └── UserDaoImpl.java
    ├── model
    │   └── User.java
    ├── service
    │   └── UserService.java
    │   └── UserServiceImpl.java
    └── main
        └── App.java

1. Model (or Entity) Layer
This layer contains the POJOs (Plain Old Java Objects) that represent the data or business entities in your application.

2. DAO (Data Access Object) Layer
This layer handles all interactions with the database.
The DAO interface defines the CRUD operations, and the implementation class (UserDaoImpl) provides the actual database logic.

3. Service Layer
The service layer contains business logic. It communicates with the DAO layer to retrieve or persist data.
The service interface defines the business operations, and the implementation (UserServiceImpl) contains the actual logic.

4. Config Layer
This package contains configuration files like database configurations,
and possibly dependency injection configurations (if using Spring or other frameworks).
-- HikariConfig

5. Main Class
The App.java is your main application class that can invoke the service methods to test the functionality.









